    "updated_at": "2012-02-16T03:18:40Z",
    "body": "Some of the changes I've been making have been geared towards keeping pairs of functions, such as:\n-  `len` / `len_bytes`,\n- `find` / `find_bytes`,\n- `slice` / `slice_bytes`, and so on.\n  I also want both `rindex` / `rindex_bytes` and `substr` / `substr_bytes`, though they aren't there at the moment.\n\nI'll gladly flip (`len`, `len_bytes`) to (`len_chars`, `len`), etc., or put one set into a submodule.  How does `str::bytes::find` or `str::chars::find` look?.  Having the byte access in the [] operator and bytestring functions will continue to be useful, but I imagine wanting to avoid thinking about bytes most of the time.\n\nThe exported stuff in str::unsafe, however, has its days numbered, especially given that we can, as you're suggesting, export less reliable but still trustworthy versions of those.\n\nI have a high tolerance for a large vocabulary of functions, so long as they can be named properly...\n",
