    "created_at": "2012-02-16T07:03:57Z",
    "updated_at": "2012-02-16T07:03:57Z",
    "body": "> How does str::bytes::find or str::chars::find look?\n\nNo, no. This isn't what I intended -- we should be using chars as things to look for and act on, almost always, and a single set of operators is probably enough (fast paths can be baked in for when arguments are <128). Just the _offsets_ that are returned should be byte offsets, with a few utilities to convert between byte and char offsets for the (rare) cases where you need characters (say, counting the # of chars between two byte offsets).\n",
